<!channel> I just checked in a model change to vroom. When Scott pushes the next build make sure you delete the version on your device before installing the new build.
<@U02895311>:   is there a way to check the status of rabbit-mq and celery?  want to make sure they are happy and running.
d'oh.. yes there is, but I need to look it up. Please hold
here is some stuff to use: sudo rabbitmqctl list_queues
that will tell the active queues. There were some other magic options that we used to use rabbit's command line but I can't find them now
ok

Listing queues ...
071e860fabb0408ab24ee5471c0db788	1
4098aae6922e4bc1a2d60f4d01d1d14d	1
5b1bff6694af404eba3071f13fccba4d	1
celery	0
worker1.ip-10-152-186-44.celery.pidbox	0
...done.
That's production....
the fact that it shows celery and worker1.xxxxx is a good sign
worker1.xxxxxx is a celery worker thread
dev has a boat load more
ok...   two more Q's.   Where are the scripts that indicate to do this hourly and what to do on the hour.
and would the output of the scripts go to a different log file?
the PushNOtifications.py script has a current_app.logger.debug() - but I never see anything in the logs from it.
celery and rabbit have their own logs. Shawn set up some aliases 'tailcelery' and 'tailrabbit'
just a second, let me look at the server code for the scripts
hah!   look at that!
thanks shawn!
the config for the hourly tasks is in app.py
there is a call to app.config.update and you can see some celery setup stuff as well as the method it calls hourly "start_pushes_new_vrooms"
great....  this has been very helpful.   thanks Matt
sure. There are some other celery tasks in there that run once a day I think (like for setting the next vroom). I don't see offhand where those get kicked off at the moment
time for me to :sleeping: :sleeping: :sleeping: :sleeping: :sleeping: :sleeping:. Grab me tomorrow and I can help look at celery tasks some more if you need it.
